Fix multiple-definition link errors under GCC's -fno-common default.

Since GCC 10 the compiler defaults to -fno-common, so a file-scope tentative
definition (no `extern`, no initializer) emits a real symbol in every
translation unit that sees it instead of being merged into one common symbol at
link time. aprx relies on the old -fcommon merging in three places:

  * aprx.h declares the pthread globals `aprsis_thread` and `pthr_attrs`
    without `extern`, so every .c that includes it (all of them) defined its
    own copy; netresolver.c additionally defined a second real `pthr_attrs`.
        multiple definition of `aprsis_thread'; aprx.o: first defined here
        multiple definition of `pthr_attrs';   aprx.o: first defined here
  * the wall-clock global `struct timeval now` is defined in both timercmp.c
    and aprx-stat.c, which are linked together into aprx-stat.
        multiple definition of `now'; aprx-stat.o: first defined here

Fix it correctly rather than forcing -fcommon: declare the shared globals
`extern` where they are pulled in from a header / second TU, and keep exactly
one real definition of each (aprsis_thread + pthr_attrs in aprsis.c, now in
timercmp.c -- which is linked into both programs). This mirrors how aprx.h
already handles the monotonic `tick` clock and leaves behaviour unchanged: one
shared object per symbol, exactly as the merged common symbol used to be.

--- a/aprx.h
+++ b/aprx.h
@@ -41,8 +41,8 @@
 
 #if defined(HAVE_PTHREAD_CREATE) && defined(ENABLE_PTHREAD)
 #include <pthread.h>
-pthread_t aprsis_thread;
-pthread_attr_t pthr_attrs;
+extern pthread_t aprsis_thread;
+extern pthread_attr_t pthr_attrs;
 #endif
 
 #ifdef _FOR_VALGRIND_
--- a/netresolver.c
+++ b/netresolver.c
@@ -13,7 +13,6 @@
 #include <signal.h>
 #include <pthread.h>
 pthread_t      netresolv_thread;
-pthread_attr_t pthr_attrs;
 #endif
 
 static int                 nrcount;
--- a/aprx-stat.c
+++ b/aprx-stat.c
@@ -18,7 +18,7 @@
 int epochtime;
 const char *aprxlogfile;	/* linkage dummy */
 const char *mycall;		/* linkage dummy */
-struct timeval now; // public wall clock that can jump around
+extern struct timeval now; // public wall clock that can jump around
 
 #ifdef ERLANGSTORAGE
 
